/**
 * This is a very smart solution to this problem.
 * The original version uses HashMaps, here I just replaced it with array to make it faster.
 * The basic idea is we use two pointers to locate the substring, and an array to store the last appearance of each chars.
 * In each run, left pointer will stay same, while right pointer will move rightward one by one. We will check the index in array to see
 * if we have encountered such char before. If it is the first time we encounter such char, then simply put the index of right pointer to it
 * (we add 1 to the value, so we would not mess with index 0 and default value in array). If we have encountered such char before, then we will update
 * value in the array to update the index of last occurrence of such char, also we need to move left pointer to the right of the index of last occurrence
 * of such char, so that we can skip previous occurrence of such char thus avoid duplicate.
 * After check the array, we can calculate the length of current substring by right pointer - left pointer +1, and update result if needed.
 *  
 * Remark:
 * when update left pointer, we need consider index stored in array as well as current index of i, so we can avoid duplicates from other chars in
 * current substring (details in comment below)
 * @author hpPlayer
 * @date May 29, 2015 7:24:56 PM
 */
